## Summary
Recover/replay `byteport-stash-1-tools-cli` by adding a proper, compilable `byteport-cli` crate as a workspace member — closing out the branch-slim hygiene work for Epic A / A12.

## Context
The `recover/byteport-stash-1-tools-cli` branch was previously triaged as closed (BRANCH_TRIAGE_DONE.md) because the original stash had a destructive Cargo.toml change and the `tools/cli/` crate didn't exist. A12 requires us to recover the intent — create a working tools CLI crate — rather than blindly replaying the broken stash.

This completes the A12 DAG unit in Epic A (Hygiene garden & branch slim) for the Compute/Infra hardening Epic.

## Changes
- Added `crates/byteport-cli/` — a new workspace member (`byteport-cli`)
- **`Cargo.toml`** (`byteport-cli`): depends on `byteport-transport` (hexagonal ports) and `clap` (derive-based CLI parser)
- **`src/main.rs`**: CLI commands for:
  - `codec` — encode/decode via `WireCodecAdapter`
  - `transport` — send/receive via `MockTransportAdapter`
  - `ui view` — render `UiView` into a terminal header
  - `ui prompt` — generate `PromptMessage` strings
- Updated workspace `Cargo.toml` to register the crate
- Updated `Cargo.lock` to reflect the new member

### Key Implementation Details
Unlike the original stash (which had a broken `Cargo.toml` with no valid path), this implementation:
- Uses the existing `byteport-transport` crate path dependency
- Wires all four hexagonal port adapters (`Codec`, `Transport`, `UiPort`, `UploadTransport`) as CLI subcommands
- Passes `cargo check --workspace`, `cargo clippy`, `cargo fmt --check`, and `cargo test`

## Testing
```bash
# Build & typecheck
cargo check -p byteport-cli

# Lint
cargo clippy -p byteport-cli

# Format check
cargo fmt -p byteport-cli --check

# Run tests
cargo test -p byteport-cli
```

All gates pass cleanly.

